# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

## Key Problems in the Original Code

| Issue | Why it breaks on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — removed in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Still exists but unreliable; throws `ThreadInterruptedException` only from managed wait states |
| `ManualResetEvent` + manual `lock` + `Queue` | Works, but is a hand-rolled producer/consumer that `Channel<T>` replaces entirely |
| Race condition | Multiple `Enqueue` calls can signal before `Dequeue` runs — only one item is dequeued per `WaitOne`/`Reset` cycle, losing events |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _runTask;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        // Task.Run replaces new Thread(); cooperative cancellation replaces Abort/Interrupt
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // ReadAllAsync drains the channel and awaits new items — no manual
        // synchronization, no lost events, no busy-waiting.
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        // TryWrite on an unbounded channel always succeeds (unless completed).
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        // 1. Signal no more items will be written
        _channel.Writer.Complete();

        // 2. Cancel the read loop (in case it's waiting for more items)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // 3. Wait for the loop to finish, with a timeout
        if (_runTask is not null)
        {
            using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
            try
            {
                await _runTask.WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Loop cancelled or timed out — acceptable during shutdown
            }
        }

        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Migration Cheat-Sheet

| .NET Framework pattern | .NET 8 replacement |
|---|---|
| `new Thread()` + `Start()` | `Task.Run()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationToken` passed to blocking calls |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue` | `Channel<T>` (or `BlockingCollection<T>`) |
| `_thread.Join(timeout)` | `await task.WaitAsync(timeout)` |
| `Thread.IsAlive` check | Inspect `task.IsCompleted` |

## Common Pitfalls

1. **`Thread.Abort()` is gone** — the single biggest breaking change. Any code path that calls it will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime, not compile time.

2. **`Channel.Writer.Complete()` vs `CancellationToken`** — you need *both*. `Complete()` tells the reader no more items are coming; the token interrupts a reader that's already waiting.

3. **The original had a race condition** — two fast `Enqueue` calls could result in only one `Dequeue` because `Reset()` clears the signal before the second item is processed. `Channel<T>` fixes this inherently.

4. **`Stop()` → `StopAsync()`** — shutdown is now async. If you must call from sync code, use `StopAsync().GetAwaiter().GetResult()`, but prefer async all the way up.

5. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable`. Failing to dispose it is a common leak in long-lived services.
